Twitter

Joel Soroos

2020-11-22

Motivation

The goal is to source and analyze Twitter posts and followers for a given Twitter account (handle) using R. We will identify tweets with most likes and retweets, as well as analyze postings over time. We will also calculate the geographic distribution of followers by accessing the Google Maps API via then visualize tables with the gt package and charts with ggplot.

1. Setup

First step is to install and load the R rtweet package by Michael Kearney.

You will then need to obtain a free Twitter API access token. Follow steps here to apply for free Twitter developer access.

We will extract Twitter data multiple times so I have created two variables to avoid duplicate entry and inconsistencies. One variable stores the Twitter handle. The other variable sample specifies the number of returned records because some Twitter accounts have large volumes of followers and tweets.

   library (rtweet)

   twitter_user <- "soroosj"
   sample <- 50

2. Source tweets

Now we will transition to extracting our first set of Twitter data, which will be tweets from our specified account.

The get_timeline function contains 90 fields on each tweet.

   library (skimr)

   tweets_raw <- get_timeline (twitter_user, n = sample)

Many of the fields are not needed for this exercise so I have culled the dataset accordingly. I have also renamed several fields for brevity and to more standard Twitter notation (i.e.likes instead of favorites).

I have decided to focus the analysis on native tweets so have filtered out retweets.

I have extracted year from the creation date to enable summarizing tweet volume by year. Also, I have truncated the Tweet text from 280 to 60 characters so fits more cleanly in a table.

   library (tidyverse)
   library (lubridate)

   tweets <- tweets_raw %>%
      filter (is_retweet == FALSE) %>%
      rename (
         likes = favorite_count,
         retweets = retweet_count,
         created = created_at
         ) %>%
      mutate (
         text = str_sub(text,1,60),
         created = as.Date(created),
         year = year(created)
         ) %>%
      select (text, year, likes, retweets, created)

We will sort by most liked tweets over time and rank via the dplyr row_to_column formula.

The gt package by Richard Iannone formats in a easy-to-read manner. The core gt::gt function adds lines between rows; many other formatting tweaks are also available but out of scope for this blog.

   library (gt)

   tweets %>%
      arrange (-likes, -retweets) %>%
      head (10) %>%
      rowid_to_column("rank") %>%
      select (-year) %>%
      relocate (rank) %>%
      gt ()

Another area of interest is how tweet activity has evolved over time. Using dplyr we can easily summarize by number of tweets with corresponding likes and retweets.

   tweets_agg <-
      tweets %>%
      group_by (year) %>%
      summarize (
         n = n (),
         likes = sum(likes),
         retweets = sum (retweets)
         ) %>%
      arrange (-year)

   tweets_agg %>%
      gt()
year n likes retweets
2020 26 112 14

We can then use Rs ggplot package to visualize by likes

   ggplot (tweets_agg, aes (x = year, y =  likes)) +
      geom_col () +
      geom_label (aes(label = likes)) +
      theme_minimal() +
      labs (x="", y = "Likes")

retweets

   ggplot (tweets_agg, aes (x = year, y =  retweets)) +
      geom_col () +
      geom_label (aes(label = retweets)) +
      theme_minimal() +
      labs (x="", y = "Retweets")

and number of tweets.

   ggplot (tweets_agg, aes (x = year, y = n)) +
      geom_col () +
      geom_label (aes(label = n)) +
      theme_minimal() +
      labs (x="", y = "Number of tweets")

3a. Source followers

  followers <- twitter_user %>%
      get_followers() %>%
      pull (user_id) %>%
      lookup_users () %>%
      select (screen_name, name, location, followers_count) %>%
      arrange (-followers_count) %>%
      rowid_to_column("rank")

3c. Obtain geographic attributes

Twitter provides a location for each user which can be converted using the Google Maps API to geographic coordinates for mapping.

ggmaps package,

   library (ggmap)

   register_google(key = Sys.getenv("GOOGLE_MAPS_API"))

   followers_geo <- followers %>%
      head (sample) %>%
      mutate_geocode (location, output = "more") %>%
      mutate (
         country = word (address, -1,-1),
         country = str_to_upper(country),
         country = ifelse(is.na(country), "NOT LISTED", country)
         ) %>%
      select (rank:followers_count, country, lon, lat) 
   
   followers_geo

3d. Followers by country

   followers_agg <- followers_geo %>%
      count (country) %>%
      arrange (-n)
   
   ggplot (followers_agg, aes (x = reorder(country, n), y = n)) +
      geom_col () +
      geom_label (aes(label = n)) +
      coord_flip () +
      theme_minimal() +
      labs (x="", y = "Followers")
